Within the overall European market, Austria exhibits characteristics similar
to Germany with packaged applications software products and turnkey systems
more dominant in the business mix.

Competition has increased steadily over the past few years.  Hardware
manufacturers invest intensively in development and distribution of software
to improve their competitive positions. They very often form cooperative
arrangements with software firms. U.S. firms often enter the market as
software suppliers with aggressive marketing techniques. EDP consultants and
data centers offer software applications to broaden their product line;
scientific institutes also enter the market as new software suppliers.

International business competition requires international computer supported
systems. Software will therefore become the determining factor in the
development of economic potential.  New technologies together with larger
markets will stimulate demand for new applications.


F.  MARKET ACCESS

The development of software in Austria for mainframes and, selected larger
super minicomputer systems, is largely handled by mainframe manufacturers
(for whom it is largely a competitive tool) and to a lesser degree by
contract software development houses. Software houses in Austria have been
able to carve out a market niche by producing specialized programs that are
intended for medical, local government and technical applications. Industrial
and commercial applications especially designed to suit particular needs also
enjoy good sales. Although sales of mainframes are growing much less swiftly
in Austria than sales of other kinds of computers, the pattern of software
distribution is not likely to change very much in the future. IBM dominates
the mainframe software market in Austria.

Major users of minicomputer software will be in the manufacturing,
government, finance, and distribution sectors. The most popular software sold
in Austria is general business administration, operating systems, data base
management, communications, word processing  graphics and calculation.
Fastest growth in this market is expected to be in multimedia and
communications software packages, though spreadsheets and graphics will be
popular as well.

The distribution of minicomputer software in Austria is conditioned by the
extent to which hardware manufacturers control their industrial market
shares. Some minicomputer suppliers, including Digital Equipment Corporation,
IBM, Hewlett-Packard, SUN Microsystems, UNISYS and AT&T, also develop their
own software, or contract with Austrian software houses to do so, and then
use their own distribution networks to market it.

Microcomputer software which is "consumer acceptable" in Austria has a long
way to go and therefore a greater reliance is placed on American-sourced
packages, which enjoy automatic credibility.

American packages, however, must meet the following criteria:
--   German language
--   inexpensive
--   portable
--   application oriented
--   simple to use and well presented

In this connection, it should be noted that Austrian computer experts agree
that in micro, minicomputer and mainframe software, the market is tilted
toward IBM. As the development of all IBM's Austrian products is in the
German language, this standard is set for other competitors.

Distribution in Austria of microcomputer software of every kind is heavily
slanted toward the various retail dealers such as hardware/software
retailers, office equipment suppliers, mail-order houses, chain stores and
department stores.

Non-tariff barriers currently present few problems for U.S. software
manufacturers exporting to the Austrian market. However, practical barriers
to U.S. software manufacturers include:
--   the need for keyboards with German accent symbols;
--   the necessity for packages to be in the German language;
--   the consumer expectation of "bug-free" programs in softwarepackages,
     especially those of foreign origin;
The need to adapt to Austrian standards and requirements in the professional
disciplines for which the software was produced.

